B.C. avian flu outbreak spreads to 29 farms
--------------------------------------------
The avian flu outbreak, restricted 2 months ago to one farm in Abbotsford,
B.C., has now leapfrogged as far as Cloverdale -­ a farming region
southeast of Vancouver -- in Surrey, raising to 29 the number of infected
farms housing almost one million birds, a federal official revealed Thursday.
"We're working extremely hard to bring this disease under control," said
Cornelius Kiley, regional veterinarian with the Canadian Food Inspection
Agency. "But without proper biosecurity, things are not moving forward as
quickly as they could. Industry and individual bird owners must take
personal responsibility. It will make the difference."
Kiley said an emergency operations staff of 150 is working on the crisis,
but emphasized staff visiting farms are using the highest biosecurity
measures and are not responsible for the continued spread of the highly
contagious virus. Unfortunately, he said, not all people [moving with] their
machinery between farms are exercising caution.
--
