Date: 16 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Star [edited]
<http://www.thestar.com/NASApp/cs/ContentServer?pagename=thestar/Layout>

More B.C. farms hit by avian flu
------------------------------------
Poultry from British Columbia's avian flu-plagued Fraser Valley has been
cleared to return to Canadian supermarket shelves while the number of farms
hit with the virus grows.
The Canadian Food Inspection Agency lifted a ban on sales of healthy
poultry outside the quarantine zone effective today. That means producers
can finally begin shipping fresh and frozen chicken and turkey products
that have been piling up in coolers for weeks.
However, the poultry can't be exported nor even enter federally registered
processors or storage sites that handle exported products.
"If the product from the Fraser Valley goes directly to an end-use grocery
store, distribution outlets that are not federally registered, then there
is no way that this product could go for export," said Dr. Cornelius Kiley,
the agency's chief B.C. veterinarian.
Some 42 countries have imposed some form of poultry ban on products from
Canada or British Columbia.
Meanwhile, 3 more poultry operations have been found with the
fast-spreading virus, raising the total to 28 from 25 since Monday. The new
sites are outside the original 10km-wide "hot zone" where the first
avian flu cases were confirmed in February 2004. "The surveillance area
doesn't exist any more," Kiley said. "We're dealing with a larger control
area. Patterns of infection have emerged since officials began battling the
highly infectious disease," he said.
"A farm in between will start out as negative but we're finding that that
farm invariably becomes positive within a few days. We continue to believe
the main route of transmission is via mechanical means, that the virus is
piggybacking on something to get there despite all the precautions being
taken."
There are about 700 commercial poultry operations in the Fraser Valley
control zone and thousands of backyard flocks, said Kiley, who warned
poultry producers to redouble their infection-control measures.
"Our collective success here is going to have to depend on very strict
biosecurity, adhered to by everyone," he said.
Officials have begun culling the Fraser Valley's 19 million birds, with
healthy birds sent to processors and then to Canadian stores. Poultry
stockpiled since the quarantine will also head to market.
"The vast majority of this fresh and frozen poultry product is likely
already processed in a way that would allow it to go directly to the
consumer," said Kiley. Fraser Valley poultry will have to be labelled in
its bulk form, but consumer labeling will depend on the processors, he
said. "I don't see any reason why it would need to be identified down to
the smallest package form. It's already been totally inspected and it's
come from perfectly normal birds."
There's no indication of how long export bans might remain in place. Kiley
said the general international guideline is 6 months after the avian flu
outbreak has been cleared and all farms have been disinfected.
Infected bird carcasses are being disposed of through composting and
incineration. A landfill near Cache Creek, about 220 kilometres northeast
of Vancouver, has been designated to take the overflow.
