Date: 16 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CBC.ca [edited]
<http://www.cbc.ca/stories/2004/04/15/canada/bcavian040415>

B.C. minister says avian flu 'not under control'
-----------------------------------------------
B.C. Agriculture Minister John van Dongen says the avian flu in the Fraser
Valley is still out of control, after new figures show 29 poultry farms are
now infected with the virus. The spread continues in spite of bio-security
measures.
Van Dongen says mobile kilns are still the preferred way to dispose of the
bird carcasses. But he says incineration and landfills are also part of the
province's containment plan.
The province has ordered the killing of 19 million birds.
Anyone going near a farm has to wear protective clothing, and health
officials are urging people to wash vehicle tires and wipe their feet
constantly on special anti-flu mats. But in spite of those measures, van
Dongen says the virus lives on.
"The problem is not under control, and the biggest difficulty we have is
moving dead birds. And if we don't get co-operation and assistance to move
these dead birds and deal with them, then the problem will continue to get
worse," he said.
The B.C. government has invoked an emergency order to have the birds
disposed of in landfills outside the control zone.
The move has angered the community of Cache Creek. Protesters, worried
about the spread of the virus, continue to block the road leading into
their waste facility. No infected poultry has been sent to them yet. But
the minister says it must remain an option because of the large number of
dead birds.
Van Dongen will meet with the mayors of communities affected by the order
on Friday. He says they all must do their part to stamp out the spread of
avian flu.
